  "Hydrogen bonding": "",
  "London dispersion forces": "",
  "Dipole-dipole forces": "",
  "London dispersion forces (LDF) arise from temporary fluctuations in electron distribution and are present in all molecules and atoms. They are the only IMF in nonpolar substances.": "",
  "Hydrogen bonding occurs when hydrogen is bonded to which of the following elements?": "",
  "C, Si, or Ge": "",
  "Any halogen": "",
  "F, O, or N": "",
  "S, P, or Cl": "",
  "Hydrogen bonds form when H is bonded to highly electronegative atoms with lone pairs: fluorine, oxygen, or nitrogen (FON). These create a strong partial positive charge on H that attracts lone pairs on neighboring molecules.": "",
  "Which substance would have the highest boiling point?": "",
  "GeH₄ (77 g/mol)": "",
  "SiH₄ (32 g/mol)": "",
  "H₂O (18 g/mol)": "",
  "CH₄ (16 g/mol)": "",
  "Despite having the lowest molar mass, H₂O has the highest boiling point due to strong hydrogen bonding between molecules. The other substances only have London dispersion forces.": "",
  "What type of IMF exists between HCl molecules?": "",
  "Dipole-dipole forces and London dispersion forces": "",
  "London dispersion forces only": "",
  "HCl is a polar molecule (dipole-dipole forces) and, like all molecules, also has London dispersion forces. It does not have hydrogen bonding because Cl is not sufficiently electronegative (not F, O, or N).": "",
  "Why does hexane (C₆H₁₄) have a higher boiling point than methane (CH₄)?": "",
  "Hexane has ionic character": "",
  "Hexane is polar while methane is nonpolar": "",
  "Hexane has stronger London dispersion forces due to more electrons and greater surface area": "",
  "Hexane has hydrogen bonds while methane does not": "",
  "Both hexane and methane are nonpolar and only have LDF. However, hexane has more electrons (50 vs 10) and greater surface area, creating stronger temporary dipoles and therefore stronger London dispersion forces.": "",
  "Which of the following liquids has the highest surface tension?": "",
  "Acetone": "",
  "Hexane": "",
  "Ethanol": "",
  "Water": "",
  "Water has the highest surface tension among common liquids due to its extensive hydrogen bonding network. Each water molecule can form up to 4 hydrogen bonds, creating strong cohesive forces at the surface.": "",
  "Ion-dipole forces are most important in which situation?": "",
  "Between two identical polar molecules": "",
  "When an ionic compound dissolves in a polar solvent like water": "",
  "Between two nonpolar molecules": "",
  "In metallic bonding": "",
  "Ion-dipole forces occur between ions and polar molecules. They are the dominant force when ionic compounds dissolve in water, as water molecules surround and stabilize the separated ions.": "",
  "Which statement about the boiling points of noble gases is correct?": "",
  "Boiling points increase going down the group due to increasing London dispersion forces": "",
  "All noble gases have the same boiling point": "",
  "Boiling points decrease going down the group": "",
  "Noble gases cannot be liquefied": "",
  "Noble gases only experience London dispersion forces. Going down the group, atomic size and electron count increase, creating stronger temporary dipoles and increasing boiling points (He: -269°C to Rn: -62°C).": "",
  "Why is the boiling point of ethanol (78°C) much higher than that of dimethyl ether (−24°C), even though they have the same molecular formula C₂H₆O?": "",
  "Ethanol can form hydrogen bonds through its O-H group, while dimethyl ether cannot": "",
  "Ethanol has a higher molecular weight": "",
  "Ethanol has stronger London dispersion forces": "",
  "Dimethyl ether is nonpolar": "",
  "Ethanol has an -OH group that can form hydrogen bonds (H bonded to O). Dimethyl ether (CH₃-O-CH₃) has no O-H or N-H bonds, so it cannot form hydrogen bonds, resulting in a much lower boiling point.": "",
  "Viscosity of a liquid generally increases with:": "",
  "Increasing temperature and weaker IMFs": "",
  "Increasing temperature and stronger IMFs": "",
  "Decreasing pressure only": "",
  "Decreasing temperature and stronger IMFs": "",
  "Viscosity increases with stronger intermolecular forces (more resistance to flow) and decreases with higher temperature (molecules move faster and overcome IMFs more easily).": "",
  "What are 'London dispersion forces'?": "",
  "The force holding atoms together within a molecule": "",
  "Forces between permanently polar molecules": "",
  "Forces between ions and polar solvents": "",
  "Temporary attractive forces caused by instantaneous dipoles from fluctuations in electron distribution, present in all molecules": "",
  "London dispersion forces (also called van der Waals forces) arise from temporary, instantaneous dipoles created by random electron movement. They increase with molecular size, electron count, and surface area.": "",
  "What does 'dipole-dipole force' mean?": "",
  "The intramolecular force within a polar bond": "",
  "The force between two nonpolar molecules": "",
  "The attraction between an ion and a polar molecule": "",
  "The attractive force between the positive end of one polar molecule and the negative end of another polar molecule": "",
  "Dipole-dipole forces are attractions between the partial positive end (δ+) of one polar molecule and the partial negative end (δ-) of another. They are stronger than LDF for molecules of similar size.": "",
  "What is a 'hydrogen bond'?": "",
  "Any bond involving hydrogen within the broader context of bond analysis": "",
  "A covalent bond between two hydrogen atoms, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "A strong dipole-dipole attraction between a hydrogen atom bonded to F, O, or N and a lone pair on a nearby F, O, or N atom": "",
  "An ionic bond between hydrogen and a halogen, as conventional bond theory would suggest": "",
  "A hydrogen bond is an especially strong dipole-dipole force occurring when H is bonded to F, O, or N (highly electronegative atoms with lone pairs). It is about 5-10% the strength of a typical covalent bond.": "",
  "What does 'polarizability' mean?": "",
  "The electronegativity difference between bonded atoms": "",
  "The ease with which the electron cloud of a molecule can be distorted to form temporary dipoles": "",
  "The permanent dipole moment of a molecule": "",
  "The ability of a substance to dissolve in water": "",
  "Polarizability measures how easily an electron cloud can be distorted. Larger atoms/molecules with more electrons are more polarizable, leading to stronger London dispersion forces.": "",
  "What is 'surface tension'?": "",
  "The tendency of a liquid to climb up a narrow tube": "",
  "The force required to break a chemical bond": "",
  "The energy required to increase the surface area of a liquid, caused by the net inward pull of intermolecular forces on surface molecules": "",
  "The pressure exerted by a gas on its container": "",
  "Surface tension results from the imbalance of intermolecular forces on surface molecules (pulled inward but not outward). Liquids with stronger IMFs (like water with hydrogen bonds) have higher surface tension.": "",
  "What does 'capillary action' refer to?": "",
  "The spreading of a drop of oil on water, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "The boiling of a liquid at reduced pressure, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "The resistance of a liquid to flow, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "The spontaneous rise or depression of a liquid in a narrow tube due to the interplay of adhesive and cohesive forces": "",
  "Capillary action occurs when adhesive forces (liquid-container attraction) compete with cohesive forces (liquid-liquid attraction). In water, adhesion to glass exceeds cohesion, causing the meniscus to rise.": "",
  "What is 'viscosity'?": "",
  "A measure of a liquid's resistance to flow, determined by the strength of its intermolecular forces": "",
  "The tendency of a liquid to form droplets": "",
  "The density of a liquid compared to water": "",
  "A measure of how easily a liquid evaporates": "",
  "Viscosity is the resistance of a fluid to flow. Liquids with strong IMFs and large, entangled molecules (like honey or motor oil) have high viscosity. Viscosity decreases with increasing temperature.": "",
  "What does 'ion-dipole force' mean?": "",
  "The force between two polar molecules": "",
  "The attractive force between an ion and the partial charge of a polar molecule": "",
  "The repulsion between like charges in solution": "",
  "The force between two ions in a crystal": "",
  "Ion-dipole forces are the attraction between an ion (full charge) and a polar molecule (partial charge). They are the primary force responsible for dissolving ionic compounds in polar solvents like water.": "",
  "What does 'vapor pressure' mean?": "",
  "The atmospheric pressure at sea level": "",
  "The pressure exerted by the vapor of a liquid in equilibrium with its liquid phase at a given temperature": "",
  "The pressure exerted by a gas above its boiling point": "",
  "The maximum pressure a container can withstand": "",
  "Vapor pressure is the pressure exerted by a vapor in dynamic equilibrium with its liquid. Substances with weak IMFs have high vapor pressures (volatile) because molecules escape the liquid easily.": "",
  "What does 'cohesion' versus 'adhesion' mean?": "",
  "Cohesion is attraction between unlike substances; adhesion is attraction between like substances": "",
  "Cohesion applies only to solids; adhesion applies only to liquids": "",
  "Both terms mean the same thing": "",
  "Cohesion is the attraction between molecules of the same substance; adhesion is the attraction between molecules of different substances": "",
  "Cohesion is the intermolecular attraction between identical molecules (water-water). Adhesion is the attraction between different molecules (water-glass). Their relative strength determines meniscus shape and capillary action.": "",
  "A gecko can walk upside down on a glass ceiling. Scientists discovered that billions of tiny hair-like structures (setae) on gecko feet maximize surface contact area. Which intermolecular force primarily allows geckos to adhere to surfaces?": "",
  "Hydrogen bonding between gecko feet and the surface": "",
  "Ionic bonds between the gecko and the glass surface": "",
  "Suction created by the setae acting like tiny cups": "",
  "London dispersion forces, which become significant when billions of setae maximize the contact surface area": "",
  "Gecko adhesion is primarily due to London dispersion forces. While individually weak, the billions of setae create an enormous contact surface area, and the cumulative LDF is strong enough to support the gecko's weight.": "",
  "A chemical engineer is designing a new waterproof coating for outdoor gear. She knows that materials with weak IMFs between the coating and water will repel water (hydrophobic). Which type of polymer surface would best repel water?": "",
  "A fluorinated polymer like PTFE (Teflon) with only weak London dispersion forces": "",
  "A polymer with many -OH groups that can hydrogen bond with water": "",
  "A polymer with ionic groups that attract water strongly": "",
  "A polymer containing many N-H bonds": "",
  "PTFE (Teflon) is nonpolar with only weak LDF between its surface and water. Since water molecules prefer to hydrogen bond with each other rather than interact weakly with the PTFE surface, water beads up and rolls off.": "",
  "A nurse administers rubbing alcohol (isopropanol) to a patient's skin before an injection. The patient feels a cooling sensation. What explains the cooling effect of evaporating alcohol?": "",
  "The alcohol creates a barrier that blocks body heat": "",
  "The highest-energy alcohol molecules escape first during evaporation, removing heat from the skin and lowering its temperature": "",
  "The alcohol reacts endothermically with the skin": "",
  "The alcohol is stored at a cold temperature": "",
  "Evaporation is endothermic. The most energetic molecules escape the liquid, absorbing heat from the skin. Alcohol evaporates faster than water (weaker H-bonding), producing a noticeable cooling effect.": "",
  "A food scientist observes that cooking oil and vinegar (aqueous acetic acid) separate into two layers in a salad dressing. When she adds an emulsifier (like egg yolk lecithin), they stay mixed. How does the emulsifier work at the molecular level?": "",
  "The emulsifier has both a polar (hydrophilic) end that interacts with vinegar and a nonpolar (hydrophobic) end that interacts with oil, bridging the two phases": "",
  "The emulsifier breaks the covalent bonds in oil molecules": "",
  "The emulsifier increases the temperature enough to dissolve oil in water": "",
  "The emulsifier reacts chemically with both oil and vinegar": "",
  "Emulsifiers are amphiphilic: one end forms hydrogen bonds/dipole interactions with the polar vinegar, while the other end interacts via LDF with the nonpolar oil. This stabilizes small oil droplets in the aqueous phase.": "",
  "An environmental scientist studies why mercury (Hg) forms nearly perfect spherical droplets on a lab bench while water spreads more. Both are liquids at room temperature. What IMF difference explains mercury's behavior?": "",
  "Mercury has very strong metallic cohesive forces between its atoms, and very weak adhesion to the bench surface, causing it to minimize surface area as spheres": "",
